[[File:Belovobaz2.jpg|right|thumb|Part of the ruins of the Belovo Basilica|alt=An ancient brick wall with a number of wide arches]]
[[File:Belovobaz5.jpg|right|thumb|Overview of the ruins|alt=A partially preserved early Christian brick basilica in the middle of a meadow with a forest in the background]]
The '''Belovo Basilica''' ({{lang-bg|<U+0411><U+0435><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0431><U+0430><U+0437><U+0438><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430>}}, ''Belovska bazilika'') is a large partially preserved [[Christianity|Christian]] [[basilica]] from [[Late Antiquity]] near the village of [[Golyamo Belovo]] in Belovo Municipality, [[Pazardzhik Province]], southwestern [[Bulgaria]]. Located on a hill in the vicinity of the village, the church dates to the 6th century and was first described in the 19th century. It features three naves and three apses as well as a baptistery. Notably, instead of a dome it is covered by a vaulted roof.

==Location and history==
The basilica is located on the Spasovitsa Hill (or Holy Savior's Hill) {{convert|1.5|km|mi}} to the south of Golyamo Belovo and {{convert|10|km|mi}} south of the town of [[Belovo, Bulgaria|Belovo]].<ref name="ivanova">{{cite web|url=http://www.focus-radio.net/?action=news&id=366904|title=<U+0411><U+0430><U+0437><U+0438><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0432> <U+043C><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+043D><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442><U+0442><U+0430> <U+201E><U+0421><U+0432><U+0435><U+0442><U+0438> <U+0421><U+043F><U+0430><U+0441><U+201D> <U+0432> <U+0411><U+0435><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0435> <U+0430><U+0440><U+0445><U+0435><U+043E><U+043B><U+043E><U+0433><U+0438><U+0447><U+0435><U+0441><U+043A><U+0438> <U+043A><U+043E><U+043C><U+043F><U+043B><U+0435><U+043A><U+0441> <U+043E><U+0442> <U+043A><U+044A><U+0441><U+043D><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0430><U+043D><U+0442><U+0438><U+0447><U+043D><U+043E><U+0441><U+0442> <U+0438> <U+0440><U+0430><U+043D><U+043D><U+043E><U+0442><U+043E> <U+0441><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+0438><U+0435>|trans_title=The basilica in the Holy Savior area is an architectural compound from Late Antiquity and the Early Middle Ages|last=<U+0418><U+0432><U+0430><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>|first=<U+041D><U+0438><U+043A><U+043E><U+043B>|date=2010-02-28|publisher=<U+0420><U+0430><U+0434><U+0438><U+043E> <U+0424><U+043E><U+043A><U+0443><U+0441>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=15 March 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xDA6jwU3|archivedate=15 March 2011}}</ref> The church is accessible via a road which starts to the east of the village and passes some of its fruit orchards.<ref name="tourism">{{cite web|url=http://www.belovo.nds-bg.org/bg/belovo/tourism.html|title=<U+0422><U+0443><U+0440><U+0438><U+0437><U+044A><U+043C>|trans_title=Tourism|publisher=<U+041D><U+0435><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+0446><U+0438><U+0430><U+043B><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0441><U+0442><U+0440><U+0430><U+043D><U+0438><U+0446><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0433><U+0440><U+0430><U+0434> <U+0411><U+0435><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+043E>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=15 March 2011|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xD9uPvvb|archivedate=15 March 2011}}</ref>

Built in the first half of the 6th century, the church has been only partially preserved to this day. Among the sections that are still standing are the north arcade, the south wall of the narthex and monumental west facade.<ref name="stamov">{{cite book|last=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0430><U+043C><U+043E><U+0432>|first=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0435><U+0444><U+0430><U+043D>|coauthors=<U+0420><U+0430><U+0448><U+0435><U+043B><U+044C> <U+0410><U+043D><U+0433><U+0435><U+043B><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>, <U+0412><U+0435><U+0440><U+0430> <U+041A><U+043E><U+043B><U+0430><U+0440><U+043E><U+0432><U+0430>, <U+041D><U+0435><U+043B><U+0438> <U+0427><U+0430><U+043D><U+0435><U+0432><U+0430><U+2013><U+0414><U+0435><U+0447><U+0435><U+0432><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430>|title=<U+0410><U+0440><U+0445><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+043D><U+043E><U+0435> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+043B><U+0435><U+0434><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+0411><U+043E><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+0438>|trans_title=The Architectural Heritage of Bulgaria|editor=<U+0421><U+0442><U+0435><U+0444><U+0430><U+043D> <U+0421><U+0442><U+0430><U+043C><U+043E><U+0432>|publisher=<U+0422><U+0435><U+0445><U+043D><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430>|location=<U+0421><U+043E><U+0444><U+0438><U+044F>|date=1972|pages=72<U+2013>73|language=Russian}}</ref> The church was first described in the 19th century by [[Bulgarian National Revival]] enlighteners Stefan Zahariev and [[Petko Slaveykov]], followed by a scholarly description by historian Petar Mutafchiev in 1915.<ref name="ivanova"/>

The earliest professional excavations of the church's ruins date to 1924.<ref name="byzantineinstitute">{{cite book|title=The Bulletin of the Byzantine Institute|publisher=Byzantine Institute of America|date=1946|volume=I|page=43}}</ref> These were financed by [[United States|American]] scholar [[Thomas Whittemore]]<ref name="angelov">{{cite book|last=Angelov|first=Dimit<U+016D>r Simeonov|title=Restoring Byzantium: the Kariye Camii in Istanbul and the Byzantine Institute restoration|publisher=Miriam and Ira D. Wallach Art Gallery, Columbia University|date=2004|page=48|isbn=9781884919152}}</ref> and carried out by art historian [[Andr<U+00E9> Grabar]].<ref name="ivanova"/> Since 1927, the church has been under state protection as a national antiquity, and in 1966 it was classified as a cultural monument of national importance.<ref name="cultmin">{{cite web|url=http://mc.government.bg/images/NPK/PAZARDGIK.pdf|archiveurl=http://www.webcitation.org/5xD81Dv7H|archivedate=15 March 2011|title=<U+0421><U+043F><U+0438><U+0441><U+044A><U+043A> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043F><U+0430><U+043C><U+0435><U+0442><U+043D><U+0438><U+0446><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043A><U+0443><U+043B><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0441> <U+043A><U+0430><U+0442><U+0435><U+0433><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F> <U+201C><U+041D><U+0430><U+0446><U+0438><U+043E><U+043D><U+0430><U+043B><U+043D><U+043E> <U+0437><U+043D><U+0430><U+0447><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438><U+0435><U+201D> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0442><U+0435><U+0440><U+0438><U+0442><U+043E><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+041E><U+0431><U+043B><U+0430><U+0441><U+0442> <U+041F><U+0430><U+0437><U+0430><U+0440><U+0434><U+0436><U+0438><U+043A> /<U+043F><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0441><U+0435><U+043B><U+0435><U+043D><U+0438> <U+043C><U+0435><U+0441><U+0442><U+0430>/|trans_title=List of monuments of culture with the category "national importance" on the territory of Pazardzhik Province by populated places|publisher=<U+041C><U+0438><U+043D><U+0438><U+0441><U+0442><U+0435><U+0440><U+0441><U+0442><U+0432><U+043E> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043A><U+0443><U+043B><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+0420><U+0435><U+043F><U+0443><U+0431><U+043B><U+0438><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F>|language=Bulgarian|accessdate=14 March 2011|page=1}}</ref> In 1994, the basilica underwent partial reconstruction.<ref name="ivanova"/>

==Architecture==
The chief material employed in the Belovo Basilica's construction were square bricks joined together with [[mortar (masonry)|mortar]]. The basilica measures  {{convert|28|x|17.15|m|ft}}. The interior is divided into three [[nave]]s by two rows of fours columns each running through the middle of the church. Each of the naves has an [[apse]] at its east end. The apses are of a semicircular design; the middle apse, the largest of the three, houses a three-tiered ''synthronon'' (stone benches for the clergy).<ref name="stamov"/>

The western section of the church includes a [[narthex]], which has a [[baptistery]] with three [[semi-dome]]s attached to its south wall. There are several entrances to the church, none of which can be considered the main entrance. The basilica is not topped by a dome. Rather, a row of [[baldachin]]-like arches which act as its roof. This feature of the basilica's architecture sets it apart from most other examples of [[early Christian architecture]] in the [[Balkans]].<ref name="stamov"/>

While architecture historian Stanford Anderson considers the ruins to be characteristic for the architecture of modern Bulgaria at the time,<ref name="anderson">{{cite book|last1=Anderson|first1=Stanford|last2=Wilson|first2=Colin St John|authorlink2=Colin St John Wilson|title=The Oxford companion to architecture|publisher=Oxford University Press|date=2009|volume=I|page=122|isbn=9780198605683}}</ref> Bulgarian archaeologist Krastyu Miyatev believes it to be radically different from Bulgaria's other preserved basilicas of the same period.<ref name="miyatev">{{cite book|last=<U+041C><U+0438><U+044F><U+0442><U+0435><U+0432>|first=<U+041A><U+0440><U+044A><U+0441><U+0442><U+044E>|title=<U+0410><U+0440><U+0445><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435><U+043A><U+0442><U+0443><U+0440><U+0430><U+0442><U+0430> <U+0432> <U+0441><U+0440><U+0435><U+0434><U+043D><U+043E><U+0432><U+0435><U+043A><U+043E><U+0432><U+043D><U+0430> <U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0438><U+044F>|publisher=<U+0411><U+044A><U+043B><U+0433><U+0430><U+0440><U+0441><U+043A><U+0430> <U+0430><U+043A><U+0430><U+0434><U+0435><U+043C><U+0438><U+044F> <U+043D><U+0430> <U+043D><U+0430><U+0443><U+043A><U+0438><U+0442><U+0435>|date=1965|page=16|language=Bulgarian|oclc=251132884}}</ref> Architecture historian Stefan Stamov likens the Belovo Basilica's plan to that of [[Mediterranean Sea|Mediterranean]] basilicas and presents the opinion that it was influenced by construction techniques from [[Asia Minor]]. The construction materials are, however, typical for the Bulgarian lands.<ref name="stamov"/>

